A big thank you to Mera, founder of Soapply for coming on LIVE and sharing the soapply story and more about The Defined Dish x Soapply impact!

Each set sold is tied to a $10 donation that funds the launch of Soapply's new water, sanitation, and hygiene projects at their newest impact zone in West Bengal, India!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
With our goal of $15,000, we will fund 3 handwashing stations, 3 drinking stations, 1 ultra-filtration water system, the construction of a toilet block, hygiene training for teachers, and a student hygiene club—tap to shop for change + help us reach our goal!

node.text:
My take on the Classic AUSTIN cocktail! 
INGREDIENTS
3 ounces Reposado Tequila (or 2 "big jiggers" full)— I use @flechaazultequila 
1.5 ounces Cointreau (or 1 "big jigger" full)
1.5 ounces fresh-squeezed lime juice (or 1 "big jigger" full)
.5 ounce martini olive brine juice (from the jar) (about 1/2 "small jigger" full)
.3 ounces fresh-squeezed orange juice (a little less than 1/2 "small jigger" full)
salt, for serving on the rim
fresh lime wedges, for serving
martini olives, for serving

INSTRUCTIONS
Fill a cocktail shaker full of ice. Add the tequila, cointreau, lime juice, olive brine, and orange juice. Close, seal and shake until very cold.
Salt the rim of just half of 2 martini glasses. Pour the martini into the glass. Serve with a wedge of lime and a few olives on a toothpick or cocktail pick.

https://thedefineddish.com/mexican-martini/

How to make SCRAPPY BONE BROTH IG tv edition. 🎥

Here is a quick demo showing how I save scraps throughout the week in a ziplock bag in my freezer so that I can make bone broth. Not only is it cheaper than buying store bought broth, but the flavor and it’s nutritional benefits are much stronger too! 
Read this blog post if you’re curious the benefits of bone broth/ what it is exactly. http://www.thedefineddish.com/bone-broth-why-and-how-i-drink-it/

Here are some very classic/traditional things I throw into my scrap bag to make bone broth: -leftover roasted chicken bones/carcass. Must be roasted, if it’s not previously roasted the flavor is ick. •celery stalks •carrots •onion scraps, shallot, etc •garlic •ginger •parsley stems •thyme, rosemary (dried or fresh works)

Throw all of those items that you have, there is not specific guidelines to what goes in. Now fill the pot until the contents are just covered with water by about 1.5 inches. Throw in a splash of apple cider vinegar, a few bay leaves, and about a tbsp black peppercorns. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to simmer and cook, covered, for 12-24 hours. 
Storing tips: strain the broth and let cool completely before storing. NOTE if you store in glass mason jars be sure it’s 100% cooled and only filled 3/4 of the way before freezing! The broth will expand and break the glass and all your hard work will be trashed 😓
You can freeze for up to 3 months. And I usually keep mine in the fridge for 7-10 days. 
FAQ:
YES you can do this in an instant pot. I’d go 180 minutes and let pressure release on its own. 
YES you can do in a crockpot, on low for 12-24 hours 
Ok, let me know your bone broth questions below!

Had the best time with my @sietefoods fam, giving them a sneak peek of a great weeknight dish from my upcoming cookbook, Chipotle Chicken Tostadas with Pineapple Salsa! 
Simple, bursting with flavor and better for you— exactly what the intention behind my book was. Checkout the full IGTV video and I’ll go ahead and give you a sneak peek of the full recipe below! And a big thank you to @sietefoods for making the best of the best and always supporting me. You have my ❤️ #

Chipotle Chicken Tostadas w/ Pineapple Slaw ⬇️ 2 c small diced fresh pineapple
¼ c finely diced red onion
1 tbsp finely diced jalapeño
2 tbsp fresh lime juice (1 lime)
1 garlic clove, minced
1 tbsp finely chopped fresh cilantro leaves
1 tsp avocado oil
½ tsp kosher salt
2 tbsp avocado oil
2 lbs ground chicken thighs
2 tsp chipotle chili powder
1 tsp kosher salt
½ tsp freshly ground black pepper
¼ c low-sodium chicken broth
1 tbsp tomato paste
6 @sietefoods Cassava Flour tortillas
2 avocados, mashed
½ c shredded purple cabbage
¼ c chopped fresh cilantro leaves

1. To make the tortillas, preheat the oven to 350°F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Place the tortillas in a single layer on the prepared baking sheet. Lightly spray the tops of the tortillas with nonstick cooking spray. Bake for 8 to 10 minutes, or until golden brown and crisp.
2. To make the salsa, toss together the pineapple, onion, jalapeño, lime juice, garlic, cilantro, avocado oil, and salt in a medium bowl. Refrigerate until ready to serve, up to 5 days. 
3. To make the chicken, heat the avocado oil over medium-high heat, in a large skillet. Add the ground chicken, chipotle chili powder, salt & pepper. Cook the chicken, breaking up the meat with the back of spoon, until it is brown, (~7 mins). Drain off any excess fat from the pan, if necessary. Reduce the heat to medium and add the chicken broth & tomato paste and stir to combine. Continue to cook for ~2 more minutes. Remove from heat & cover to keep warm until ready to serve.

3-Ingredient Chili-Cheese Enchiladas!! 
Serves 4

Ingredients:
1 16.9-oz carton Kettle & Fire Bone Broth Beef Chili With Beans Soup
8 grain-free tortillas
1 8-oz block Monterey jack cheese (Slice ¾ of the block into ¼-inch slices, shred the remaining ¼ of the block)
Optional: Green onions, sliced for garnish

Method:
Preheat the oven to 375 degrees fahrenheit. 

In a 2 ½ quart (or 9x13) baking dish, pour in ¼ of the carton of chili and spread to cover the bottom.

One at a time, place the tortillas in a dry (no oil) stainless steel skillet over medium heat and warm for about 30 seconds on each side to make them more pliable. Once warmed, place two slices of cheese on each tortilla, gently roll it up, and place it seam side down in the baking dish.

Once all the enchiladas are rolled, pour the remaining chili over the enchiladas and spread to coat evenly. Top with the shredded Monterey Jack.

Cover with foil and bake for 15 minutes. Remove the foil and bake until the cheese is golden brown, 8 to 10 minutes.

Remove from the and sprinkle with the green onions, if using. Enjoy!!!

If you followed along on our Hawaii trip, you saw that Clayton became quite the Mai Tai connoisseur! We decided to play around with the recipe at home so you can bring vacation right into your kitchen. You’ll just need a bottle of @cointreau_us, two types of rum, lime juice and orgeat syrup — a sweet almond syrup — and you’ll be ready to go. Add a wedge of pineapple and you’ll be in vacation mode in no time! #cointreaucollective

Mai Tai
Serves 2
1 oz Cointreau
2 oz aged rum
2 oz white rum
2 oz fresh lime
juice
1 ½ oz orgeat syrup

Pour all ingredients in a shaker. Add ice and shake until very cold. Strain into a glass filled with ice. Garnish with a pineapple wedge with a pineapple leaf, if desired. Mint is also popular.

Cheers!

Rise and shine with these delicious Breakfast Granola Muffins, perfect for a grab-and-go breakfast with a cup of coffee! #ad They are easy to make and flavored beautifully with @purely_elizabeth Grain-Free Vanilla Almond Butter Granola + a bright pop of orange zest, a sweet touch from the dates.

The granola combines rich almond butter with superfood seeds, coconut sugar and hints of vanilla for irresistible grain-free clusters that work perfectly in this breakfast muffin. Get 25% off all products on purelyelizabeth.com using code ALEX!

(Makes 12)
Non-stick cooking spray (I use avocado oil spray)
2 large eggs
½ cup pure maple syrup
½ cup unsweetened, full fat coconut milk 
¼ cup liquid coconut oil or avocado oil
2 tsp pure vanilla extract
½ tsp ground cinnamon
1 ½ cup super-fine almond flour
1 cup tapioca flour
2 tsp baking powder
½ tsp baking soda
¼ tsp kosher salt
½ cup granola, roughly chopped into smaller pieces, plus more for topping
1 tbsp orange zest
4 pitted medjool dates, minced

Preheat the oven to 350 degrees and grease a muffin tin with nonstick spray (or line with muffin liners). 

In a large mixing bowl, combine the eggs, maple syrup, coconut milk, oil, and vanilla extract. Whisk until very well combined and frothy. 

Add the cinnamon, almond flour, tapioca flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt. Stir until very well combined and there are no lumps. 

Fold in the granola, orange zest, and minced dates and stir once more until evenly distributed. 

Evenly distribute the batter into 12 muffin cups, about ¾ way full. Sprinkle each of the muffins with a bit more of the granola. Transfer to the preheated oven and bake until a toothpick inserted comes out clean, about 12-14 minutes.

#purelybreakfastclub #eatpurely

Want something healthy but ya need something hearty? Try my Southern-Style Hamburger Steaks with Mushroom and Onion Gravy over some mashed potatoes! 

This recipe, inspired by my grandma, Nonnie- Is a #whole30 compliant dinner that the fam will flip out over! 

Also if you’re not from the south your likely wondering— isn’t this Salisbury steak? Consider it a southern cousin to Salisbury Steak. The difference really isn’t much other than the fact that Salisbury Steaks have a bit more “fancy” ingredients in it like breadcrumbs, bell peppers, and more whereas a hamburger steak is just a simple beef patty smother in a fantastic onion gravy. 

You can find the full recipe on my blog, linked in my bio! 

https://thedefineddish.com/southern-style-hamburger-steak-with-onion-and-mushroom-gravy/

node.text:
This Coconut Lime Chicken is a fantastic dinner to add to your rotation! 

Inspired by a dish on the Cheesecake Factory menu, this dish is filled with tender pieces of chicken, snow peas, mushrooms and onions smothered in a delicious Thai-inspired Coconut-lime sauce with mangos and cashews. It’a a little spicy, a little savory, and a little sweet– making it a total winner around the table.

You can keep this dish Whole30 by serving it alone or over cauliflower rice. But if you aren’t doing a Whole30, it’s fantastic over steamed, white rice.

Find the full recipe on the blog, linked in my bio: 

https://thedefineddish.com/coconut-lime-chicken/

This Whole30 Enchilada Skillet is one of the best and easiest Whole30 dinners! 

I totally understand that cauliflower rice gets a bad rep. I agree, it’s bland and watery! But toss it up with seasoned ground beef and an enchilada sauce— and it totally comes to life in a lovely way! Just trust me, this is an old one but a very popular one from the blog!

This easy Baked Honey-Ginger Salmon is a great weeknight dinner with impressive flavor! 

Beautiful, center-cut salmon is drizzled with an Asian-inspired honey-ginger sauce and baked until it is cooked through and flakey. I love serving this with a green bean stir fry and steamed white rice for a complete meal; however, it really pairs nicely with most veggies and salads! 

Find this simple recipe by tapping the link in my bio: 

https://thedefineddish.com/honey-ginger-baked-salmon/

node.text:
These Grain-Free “Hostess” Cupcakes are the perfect way to brighten your day! 

As we head back to school, I’m nostalgic for the kinds of snacks that used to fill my lunchbox. If you are not familiar, a “Hostess” Cupcake is a packaged devil’s food cupcake, filled with a vanilla marshmallow creme and topped with chocolate ganache then a signature white chocolate swirl!

We recreated the childhood favorite but made it grain and refined sugar-free. They are rich and deeply chocolatey and even better the next day… making them the perfect treat to make ahead and enjoy all week long. 

Tap the link in my bio for the full recipe 

https://thedefineddish.com/grain-free-hostess-cupcakes/

node.text:
Breakfast quesadilla filled with: 

• @applegate no sugar bacon 
• @vitalfarms scrambled eggs 
• @lavonfarms butter 
• @sietefoods Cassava flour tortillas 
• @rumianocheese 
• avocado 

Cook the bacon and scrambled 2 eggs. Set aside. 

Melt butter in the skillet and add one of the tortillas and start piling up the ingredients: I sprinkled the cheese, spread the eggs, crumbled the bacon and added avocado to half (Sutton isn’t a fan), sprinkled a bit more cheese to clue on the top tortilla and cook over medium heat until golden brown and crisp, 3-4 mins. Use a sturdy spatula and flip, continue to cook on the other side until golden brown and crisp, 3 more mins. 

Transfer to a cutting board, slice, and serve with your fave hot sauce. Enjoy! You can really make these as fancy or as simple as you’d like! Get creative!
